{"timestamp": "2025-11-29 17:27:11.455649", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — SDN spine–leaf lab\nSummary assessment\n- Network health: Major outage for tenant (10.0.0.0/24) traffic. Hosts on the 10.0.0.0/24 subnets cannot reach each other; L2/L3 forwarding between hosts is not functioning.\n- Scope: All leaf and spine OVS switches (leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1) are not forwarding host traffic (affects all hosts host_1_1..host_2_2). Management plane (ICMP to controller) is reachable from switches, but the SDN control plane (OpenFlow session) is failing.\n- Severity: High — tenant connectivity broken due to missing dataplane forwarding rules on switches.\n\nKey anomalous observations (evidence)\n1) Host-to-host reachability failures\n- Pings between hosts all fail with \"Destination Host Unreachable\" reported by the source host:\n  - host_1_1 -> host_1_2 / host_2_1 / host_2_2: 100% loss; \"Destination Host Unreachable\".\n  - host_1_2 -> host_2_1 / host_2_2: 100% loss; \"Destination Host Unreachable\".\n  - host_2_1 -> host_2_2: 100% loss; \"Destination Host Unreachable\".\n- ARP/neighbor state on a host shows incomplete/FAILED entries:\n  - host_1_1: ip neigh / arp -n show 10.0.0.2/3/4 incomplete and entries marked FAILED/incomplete.\n\nInterpretation: hosts can transmit but receive no ARP replies / no L2 reachability — indicates switching/forwarding failure on the leaf switches.\n\n2) Switch datapath / controller state\n- All OVS bridges have a controller configured but show the controller connection status as disconnected/backoff:\n  - leaf_1 controller status: target \"tcp:20.0.0.100:6633\", is_connected = false, status: last_error=\"Connection refused\", state=BACKOFF\n  - leaf_2 same: last_error=\"Connection refused\", state=BACKOFF\n  - spine_1 same: last_error=\"Connection refused\", state=BACKOFF\n- ovs-ofctl show outputs:\n  - For leaf_1 and leaf_2, LOCAL (internal) interface is shown PORT_DOWN / LINK_DOWN (speed 0) in the ofctl output. Physical ports (eth0/eth1/eth2) show link up (10GB-FD).\n- ovs-ofctl dump-flows produced no flows on the switches (NXST_FLOW reply empty).\n\nInterpretation: switches have no controller session and no controller-populated flows. Because the bridges are configured fail_mode: secure (seen in ovs-vsctl show), OVS will not act as a standalone learning switch — packets without matching flows are dropped.\n\n3) Controller reachability / service\n- ICMP reachability: spine_1 can ping the controller (20.0.0.100) — e.g. ping 20.0.0.100 succeeded with low latency — management network connectivity exists.\n- TCP OpenFlow port check from a switch (spine_1) to the controller:\n  - A TCP connection attempt to 20.0.0.100:6633 returned \"closed\". (>/dev/tcp/20.0.0.100/6633 => closed)\n- netstat/ss on the switch did not show an established controller connection; ovs-vsctl reports last_error \"Connection refused\".\n\nInterpretation: network path to controller is up (ICMP OK) but the OpenFlow endpoint on 20.0.0.100 is not accepting connections (port closed / controller process not listening on configured port), so OVS cannot establish control sessions.\n\nFault localization\n- Primary service/device implicated: SDN controller service on 20.0.0.100 (OpenFlow listener on tcp:6633) — currently not accepting OpenFlow connections (port closed).\n- Secondary impacted devices: All OVS switches (spine_1, leaf_1, leaf_2). They are configured to use the controller (controller configured), and their fail_mode is secure. Because the controller connection is refused, switches have no control-plane sessions and no flows, and thus dataplane forwarding is effectively disabled for unknown packets.\n- Affected endpoints: All hosts host_1_1, host_1_2, host_2_1, host_2_2 — they cannot ARP each other and cannot exchange traffic.\n\nRoot-cause analysis (logical chain)\n1. The SDN controller's OpenFlow listener (tcp:20.0.0.100:6633) is not accepting TCP connections (verified: TCP connect => closed), despite ICMP reachability to 20.0.0.100. This indicates the controller service (or its OpenFlow listener) is down or listening on a different port/address.\n2. Each OVS bridge (spine_1, leaf_1, leaf_2) is configured to connect to that controller but receives \"Connection refused\" and is in BACKOFF/is_connected=false. Therefore no OpenFlow session is established.\n3. The bridges are configured fail_mode: secure. In secure mode, when the controller is disconnected, the switch does not operate as a normal standalone learning switch; packets without matching flows are dropped.\n4. Because there are no controller-supplied flows and no local fallback forwarding, L2 learning/ARP traffic is dropped at the leaf switches. Hosts cannot learn each other's MACs or receive ARP replies — resulting in complete host-to-host connectivity failure on 10.0.0.0/24.\n\nRelevant command output excerpts (evidence pointers)\n- Host ping failures: \"From 10.0.0.1 icmp_seq=1 Destination Host Unreachable\" (host->host pings).\n- ARP / neighbor: host_1_1 shows \"10.0.0.2 dev eth0 FAILED\" and ARP incomplete entries.\n- OVS controller status: ovs-vsctl get-controller leaf_1 => \"tcp:20.0.0.100:6633\" and list controller shows status last_error=\"Connection refused\", is_connected=false, state=BACKOFF.\n- ovs-ofctl show leaf_1: LOCAL(leaf_1): addr:... config: PORT_DOWN state: LINK_DOWN (speed 0) while physical ports show \"10GB-FD COPPER\".\n- No flows present: ovs-ofctl dump-flows returned empty replies.\n- Controller TCP check from switch: bash -c '>/dev/tcp/20.0.0.100/6633' returned \"closed\".\n- Ping from spine_1 to 20.0.0.100 succeeded (ICMP works): \"64 bytes from 20.0.0.100 ...\"\n\nConclusions\n- The immediate cause of tenant host connectivity loss is the lack of an active OpenFlow connection between switches and the controller combined with the switches’ fail_mode=secure, which prevents fallback forwarding.\n- The origin of the problem is the SDN controller service (or its OpenFlow listener) not accepting connections on the configured port (20.0.0.100:6633), not a pure network path failure (ICMP to controller is OK).\n- All switches are affected (spine_1, leaf_1, leaf_2) because they all point to the same controller and none has local flows to forward host traffic.\n\nIf further evidence is required, I can gather additional targeted outputs (controller-side listen status if access is available, detailed ovsdb controller status timestamps, flow table dumps, or tcpdump on a leaf port to show ARP packets being dropped). (Note: I will not propose mitigation steps unless you ask for them.)", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 35432, "output_tokens": 2917, "total_tokens": 38349, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 35328}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1280}}}
